+
+So, I'll structure it like this:                            
+
+ • Commit: Each commit will have an ID, a parentId (or null 
+   for the root), and a data map of docId to versionId.     
+ • Branch: Each branch will point to a specific Commit.     
+ • Versions: A global store mapping versionId to the actual 
+   Version content.                                         
+
+The update operation will create a new version of the       
+document, then create a new commit as a child of the current
+branch's head.                                              
+
+The three-way merge will involve:                           
+
+ 1 Finding the common ancestor of the current branch and the
+   source branch.                                           
+ 2 Comparing the data at the ancestor, the current state    
+   ("ours"), and the source branch state ("theirs").        
+ 3 For each document, performing a structural merge on its  
+   content.                                                 
+
+The requirement that the documents are plain JSON objects   
+with no top-level arrays is critical. This impacts my deep  
+merge logic. I need to recursively handle nested objects:   
+
+ • If a field exists in all three (base, ours, theirs):     
+    • If ours == theirs, no change.                         
+    • If ours != base, and theirs == base, take ours.       
+    • If ours == base, and theirs != base, take theirs.     
+    • If ours != base, theirs != base, and ours != theirs,  
+      then a conflict.                                      
+
+Since "structural merge" and the path being a "dot-separated
+JSON path" implies I should recurse through object          
+structures.                                                 
+
+Time to implement.[0m
